WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I had a strange dream the other day. I dreamed that while browsing in a bookshop, I ran into

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:17.560
[Amit Varma]: the me of 1990 from 30 years ago. He's 16 years old. I'm 46. He was walking around in

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:22.760
[Amit Varma]: the street in 1990 and walks into this bookstore, which magically also has another door leading

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:28.140
[Amit Varma]: out to 2020. The poor lad is bewildered by the books here. I watch him barely as he opens

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:32.220
[Amit Varma]: one book to that early page in which the date of publishing is written. And then he steps

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:36.180
[Amit Varma]: back in shock and horror. He turns around to see who else is there. But I'm the only

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:41.900
[Amit Varma]: one there. Our eyes meet, but he doesn't know he is me 30 years later. No doubt he imagines

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:47.400
[Amit Varma]: his future self differently. And as I now remember, he also imagines his present self

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:51.800
[Amit Varma]: differently from what it is. I look at him with jealousy. He's so slim with all his life

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:57.360
[Amit Varma]: ahead of him. I look at him with revulsion. I remember who I was my anxieties and my prejudices,

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:01.980
[Amit Varma]: my unearned arrogance, my foolish vanity. I look at him with pity. He will take so long

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:06.160
[Amit Varma]: to learn so little and then it might be too late. And meanwhile, the poor lad is trapped

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:11.360
[Amit Varma]: in the future. As I am lost in these thoughts, I see him turn around and walk towards me.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:17.140
[Amit Varma]: I recoil in horror because at that moment, as his young eyes meet mine, it strikes me

00:01:17.140 --> 00:01:27.720
[Unknown]: that he is less of a stranger to me than I am to myself. Welcome to the scene and the

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:32.040
[Unknown]: unseen. Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:39.160
[Amit Varma]: host Amit Verma. Welcome to the scene and the unseen. I'm often amazed by how much the

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:44.360
[Amit Varma]: world has changed in the last 30 years, perhaps more than in any other 30 year span in history.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Technology, social media, globalization have all transformed our society. We normalize

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:54.480
[Amit Varma]: change so quickly. So yesterday's miracle is often today's banal. Yesterday's magic

00:01:54.480 --> 00:02:00.360
[Amit Varma]: is today's science. So some of us don't even realize how much we have changed and are changing.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:05.200
[Amit Varma]: I explored some of this territory in episode 137 of the scene and the unseen in which the

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: great columnist Santosh Desai shared his insights on the changes in our society in the last

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:16.200
[Amit Varma]: 30 years. And my guest today is Paromita Vora, another columnist who never fails to take

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:21.760
[Amit Varma]: me deeper into myself. So much of her work makes me look at the familiar with new eyes

00:02:21.760 --> 00:02:26.120
[Amit Varma]: and new eyes. In fact, is a theme of some of her work. Paromita has made films, written

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:32.040
[Amit Varma]: many columns, created installations and open minds. Also, she brings to all her work a

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:37.240
[Amit Varma]: lens that is different from the male gaze of men with beards, as she calls them, which

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:42.360
[Amit Varma]: misses as much as it sees. And as the show is called the scene and the unseen, how could

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:46.000
[Amit Varma]: I have a better guest on it than Paromita? Welcome to the show, Paro.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.000
[Guest]: Hi, thank you.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:53.600
[Amit Varma]: So, Paro, before we sort of get down to your work and all the weighty themes of this episode,

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:57.480
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about yourself. What's your journey like? What did the seven-year-old

00:02:57.480 --> 00:02:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Paro want to be?

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:02.680
[Guest]: I think I wanted to be a librarian when I was seven years old. I seem to remember that.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:08.760
[Guest]: Which is a little bit like a drunk wanting to own an alcohol shop, right? I just I wanted

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:12.800
[Guest]: unlimited access to books like many of us at that age in that era.

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:14.840
[Guest]: Where was this? Where were you born and brought up?

00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:18.000
[Guest]: I was born in Pune, but I was brought up in many different places because my father was

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.920
[Guest]: in the Air Force. And in fact, one of the things wherever I went was to find the local

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:28.240
[Guest]: lending library and become a member. And when I was seven, we were actually posted in Hyderabad

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:34.280
[Guest]: in Sikandarabad, which is a beautiful cantonment town and full of a sense of Enid Blyton like

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:38.000
[Guest]: mystery. Because, you know, since it's a cantonment town, it still has all those old colonial

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.840
[Guest]: buildings with very high ceilings. And I don't know if there's a secret passage behind this

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:44.480
[Guest]: room and all of that.

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:46.560
[Amit Varma]: All famous five and five letters.

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:50.760
[Guest]: And my brain was definitely chock full of having read all that stuff. And I wanted more

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:55.280
[Guest]: than anything to have a secret club, except I didn't have too many friends. And there

00:03:55.280 --> 00:04:01.160
[Guest]: was a very old colonial club called the Sikandarabad Club, and it had a separate room, which was

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:06.360
[Guest]: a children's library, like almost like a little house inside some what felt like a forest

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:12.480
[Guest]: to me. When I saw it as a grown up, I was like, oh, it's just a few plants. And there

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:17.800
[Guest]: was a very elderly or seemed elderly to me at that time, Anglo Indian lady who ran the

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:24.600
[Guest]: library. I was a bit scared of her, but she sort of took to this funny kid who would come

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:27.320
[Guest]: every day. Every day I would go to the library for a new book, right?

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:28.800
[Guest]: Were you the only kid who would go every day?

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:32.040
[Guest]: I think I was the only kid who used to go to the library, maybe. I mean, there was a

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:36.760
[Guest]: shelf of Nancy Drew's and Hardy Boys and you know, that sort of thing.

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And you read both.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:41.560
[Guest]: So I read both. I read all very quickly. And I might have been the only kid who was reading

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:46.160
[Guest]: the other books in the library, right? And she was very sweet. I was scared of her, but

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:49.720
[Guest]: now when I look back, she was very sweet, always looking for books to give me. And I

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:55.320
[Guest]: guess this was my idea of heaven as an odd child who didn't have a lot of friends, who

00:04:55.320 --> 00:05:00.720
[Guest]: was a little peculiar and a bit of a misfit. So I obviously felt like when I grow up, if

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:03.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm a librarian, I'll always be at home.

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:07.400
[Amit Varma]: And what is that kind of moment where you discover a different kind of literature from

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:11.440
[Amit Varma]: the children's literature? Like I remember for me, it was like I was very privileged

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.880
[Amit Varma]: in the sense my father had thousands of books at home. And one day I stumbled upon a book

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:18.640
[Amit Varma]: titled The House of the Dead. And of course, it seemed like a nice adventure book. And

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:24.040
[Amit Varma]: I picked it up. And it was Dostoevsky's account of his time in prison in Siberia. And I was

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:27.520
[Amit Varma]: completely hooked. So that's kind of, you know, I can remember that as a moment that

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:30.440
[Amit Varma]: changed everything for me. Was it a similar sort of?

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:37.320
[Guest]: So I mean, I don't have such a precise memory, but I do think that this voraciousness is

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:42.000
[Guest]: a way that you, like your life changes because your appetite is constantly leading you to

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.520
[Guest]: look for more and more things. And my parents had a lot of books and all the books used

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:51.800
[Guest]: to be kept in the study room, which had the television. So and you didn't really, I mean,

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:57.320
[Guest]: back in the 70s, you watch TV once a week for the Sunday movie or Chitrahaar or whatever.

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:01.240
[Guest]: So that room itself used to feel like a mystery room because you didn't go in there very often.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:05.480
[Guest]: Nobody was staying in that room. And that bookshelf, once I'd finished all my books,

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:09.080
[Guest]: I obviously would keep looking. I must confess that the book I remember most was some kind

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:14.760
[Guest]: of a porno I found, I think. But yes. And then I got caught reading it and got whacked

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:19.720
[Guest]: also. But I mean, I think the first grownup book that I remember reading, though I don't

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:24.480
[Guest]: remember the book now, was Of Mice and Men. And I do think there's something fantastic

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:30.280
[Guest]: about reading something you don't really get. But knowing, you know, there is something

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:35.320
[Guest]: to get here. You know, there is that feeling of mystery and excitement and adventure and

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:38.400
[Guest]: gives you something to look forward to and push towards that I want to become the person

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:42.840
[Guest]: who understands that book. And so you start looking for other books along the way. And

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:47.440
[Guest]: I think in the same way, a little bit later, we were posted in Baghdad. My dad was posted

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:49.640
[Guest]: in Baghdad. And there was a Kendra Vidyalaya there.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:50.640
[Amit Varma]: Kendra Vidyalaya in Baghdad?

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:55.560
[Guest]: Yes. And in fact, you know, in the Kendra Vidyalaya, because I had studied in the South,

00:06:55.560 --> 00:07:00.240
[Guest]: my Hindi was horrible. And I was like, I cannot study Sanskrit. Like Hindi is bad enough,

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:06.840
[Guest]: but now suddenly, so I cried and cried and I was somehow excused. And my Sanskrit teacher

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:11.280
[Guest]: refused to take that lying down. And she said, I'll give you extra classes in Sanskrit.

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:15.600
[Guest]: And I'm very grateful to her because Sanskrit is a pretty systematic language. And because

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:19.400
[Guest]: now I see that I'm a conceptual thinker, so I really took to it. And my Hindi teacher

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:24.760
[Guest]: was very upset because I got like 100 on 100 in Sanskrit and some 5 on 10 or whatever 50%

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:28.840
[Guest]: in Hindi. And she felt betrayed by all of this. But I feel that my teachers at that

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:35.600
[Guest]: time also, teachers take an interest in the odd kids who they feel are bookish. And my

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:39.680
[Guest]: teachers gave me many books. So I remember that my social studies teacher gave me Alex

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:45.080
[Guest]: Haley's Roots, when I must have been 11 or something. So again, while reading it, I of

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:48.040
[Guest]: course understood that book, it was not so hard to understand. But it was a little bit

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:52.120
[Guest]: more grown up than the stage I was at. But I think all of those things, yes, did help

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:57.520
[Guest]: me know that the world is a very complex and interesting and different place. And all the

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:01.080
[Guest]: places I'm not supposed to go are the places I should definitely go and check out.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:05.800
[Amit Varma]: No, and it strikes me that back in those days, 70s, 80s, for a curious, imaginative Indian

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:09.640
[Amit Varma]: kid, which I also was in the 80s, I can remember there's really not much to do. You read books,

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:14.760
[Amit Varma]: if you're fortunate enough to have books available to you, read them. But today there is so much.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:18.560
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you to take sort of a step out of yourself for a moment and imagine the seven

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:23.280
[Amit Varma]: year old Paromita or the 10 year old Paromita in today's times. Is she still reading as

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:25.960
[Amit Varma]: much? What is she doing? How is she driven?

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:30.720
[Guest]: I think a seven year old version of me probably would not exist very easily. Well, maybe they

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:35.760
[Guest]: do exist. I think I don't think that a seven year old today would be reading as much. But

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:42.880
[Guest]: I don't think that they're any different in terms of a sense of curiosity. In fact, you

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:49.080
[Guest]: know, the strange coexistence in India, especially of how on the one hand, kids are very separate

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:55.000
[Guest]: from adults. But on the other hand, they're all mixed up in adult life. I think it creates

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.960
[Guest]: a particular kind of condition. So I do think that seven year olds today are both very grown

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:04.800
[Guest]: up in some of the things they understand in ways that we certainly weren't. We were a

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:11.200
[Guest]: little bit more lost in the woods. But I think there is still a sense of mystery and science

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:15.080
[Guest]: that they're very interested in. I think certainly if I was seven today, I would be a little

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:20.520
[Guest]: bit more interested in doing experiments and learning how things work because YouTube is

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:24.520
[Guest]: the new library, right? I mean, the internet is a new library for kids. And I think they

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:27.840
[Guest]: are discovering varied things in it in their own way.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:32.320
[Amit Varma]: Can we explore the thought a little bit further? Like when you talk about how adult life is

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:37.800
[Amit Varma]: much more interspersed with childhood life than it was then, is that in some ways maybe

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:42.320
[Amit Varma]: a threat to the innocence of childhood? Or what does it mean for the experience of childhood?

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:46.640
[Guest]: You know, I am not a fan of this innocence of childhood idea. I don't think that children

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:51.920
[Guest]: are any more or less innocent than anybody else. I mean, I perceive myself as a very

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:56.480
[Guest]: innocent person still. So I think innocence is a quality that all of us have. And some

00:09:56.480 --> 00:10:01.720
[Guest]: of us hold on to it till we die. And some of us don't. And one of the reasons that we

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:08.080
[Guest]: don't is because innocence has a certain vulnerability involved, right? And when I say innocent,

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:15.360
[Guest]: I don't mean naive or unknowing of the world, right? But rather that you're willing to be

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:20.120
[Guest]: surprised, rather that you're willing to imagine, like, going to something anew.

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:21.440
[Amit Varma]: You're not jailed.

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:26.720
[Guest]: Yes. So one of my favorite pieces of writing actually is William Blake's songs of innocence

00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:31.800
[Guest]: and experience. And for me, it was a very novel idea when I read it that, well, being

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:36.040
[Guest]: innocent is not the same as being good. To know and then be good is very different than

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:40.760
[Guest]: to be virtuous by not knowing anything and maintaining innocence, right? So I'm not using

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:45.880
[Guest]: innocence in that way, but I'm using it in the sense of being open and vulnerable and

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:50.200
[Guest]: going in with a childlike curiosity and willingness to be delighted by something.

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:55.060
[Guest]: That's why, you know, one of my dhaadiwala irritations is the way in which people speak

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:56.760
[Guest]: as if they already know everything.

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:59.760
[Guest]: Yeah, the men with beard syndrome you have often written about.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:04.160
[Guest]: Yes, yes. And you know, Twitter has given so much play to that tendency. So somebody

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:09.040
[Guest]: will always say, oh, this is just happening because, you know, the liberal does this and

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:13.880
[Guest]: now the right wing is doing that and now this thing and that thing. And yeah, I don't disagree.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:18.280
[Guest]: But I also feel that if we can so neatly wrap everything up, then there's nothing left to

00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:22.360
[Guest]: really learn in the world. And that is never true. There's always something new happening

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:26.360
[Guest]: at every moment. And innocence requires being open to that possibility rather than saying

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:29.360
[Guest]: that I know what everything is.

00:11:29.360 --> 00:11:34.360
[Guest]: I think the opposite of innocence is a kind of fear, which is if I don't already know

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:38.200
[Guest]: everything, then who am I? What am I? Like, you know, what's my role? So I think there

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:43.160
[Guest]: is that. But to go back to your question about the interspersing of adult and child, you

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:48.480
[Guest]: know, I think that it's actually not so much as it threatens children's innocence, but

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:53.480
[Guest]: it threatens their individuality. You know, the possibility of being bored, which is something

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:58.280
[Guest]: we are talking about as children, that you had to make your own entertainment. So you

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:03.240
[Guest]: kind of always were getting into places you were not supposed to. You inserted yourself

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:08.400
[Guest]: into adult life, tried to watch movies that were forbidden to you, tried to read your

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:14.400
[Guest]: parents' books, eavesdropped way too much on adult conversations in an effort to entertain

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:21.320
[Guest]: yourself as much as curiosity about what's forbidden. And I think today adults insert

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:27.960
[Guest]: themselves into children's lives too much. They want to pre-decide. And in a society

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:33.960
[Guest]: which already pre-decides so much, you know, in terms of our identity, so much is already

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:39.440
[Guest]: set out for the kind of life that we might end up having. Now there's an extra layer

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:45.520
[Guest]: of it that your kid is going to like, you know, parenting as an idea has taken hold

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:50.360
[Guest]: of middle-class India in a very big way. And especially with more nuclear families, the

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:55.000
[Guest]: tendency of parents to be involved in their children's lives to the extent where children

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:02.040
[Guest]: don't really have a strong sense of privacy, individuality, fallow time, a place basically

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:06.080
[Guest]: to become yourself. Because that's really what that time is, that you figure yourself

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest]: out as you go along, because nobody's really paying that much attention to you. And I think

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.960
[Guest]: paying too much attention to children is binding adults and children in some kind of an unhealthy

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:23.040
[Guest]: circle where, I mean, how do you also grow older if you're all the time in the role of

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:27.640
[Guest]: parenting, right? Because becoming older is also a pleasurable new experience. I can say

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:31.280
[Guest]: now that I'm growing older, it's because it's completely different. It's an unknown world.

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:34.000
[Amit Varma]: That really gives me hope because I'm terrified of it. And yet it's happening.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:40.320
[Guest]: I think it's fantastic because you do change and you don't know you. You have the chance

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:45.200
[Guest]: to get to know yourself all over again in different phases of your life. And honestly,

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:49.360
[Guest]: the biggest romance you'll ever have in your life is with yourself. So this newness of

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:54.400
[Guest]: you and even the fact that you're slower or that you think differently, you don't automatically

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:59.160
[Guest]: know all the popular culture. I was terrified of this happening to me because I love popular

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:03.080
[Guest]: culture. And now that I don't automatically know all of it, it's actually pretty okay

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:08.680
[Guest]: because there are some new things that I know or some harder things that I want to do, that

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:12.360
[Guest]: I feel able to do. And this is all a kind of new discovery of myself and through that

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: a new discovery of the world and other people, right? But I think if you lock yourself into

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:23.080
[Guest]: that role of parenting, then this kind of a stunting happens of both parents and children.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:30.800
[Guest]: So I think that childhood then doesn't become the place from which you grew up as it ought

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:36.680
[Guest]: to be. And I do see that replicated in a lot of young people's lives, a lot of young people

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:41.600
[Guest]: that I encounter, that there is also a desire to please the parents over much. There is

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:47.320
[Guest]: a desire to excel very fast in a way that is not possible when you're very young. You

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:52.720
[Guest]: need that time to become good at something, to learn. The importance of being unimportant,

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:58.920
[Guest]: in other words, has really been devalued, right? Because to not matter all that much

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:06.600
[Guest]: gives you the freedom to make mistakes and meander. But to all the time be in somebody's

00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:13.200
[Guest]: gaze is suffocating. And I feel that is really the loss that some childhoods are experiencing.

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:16.880
[Amit Varma]: That's a very profound thought. And it also brings me to the question like both what you

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:22.180
[Amit Varma]: said about children suddenly having parents much more involved in growing up and also

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:26.080
[Amit Varma]: in the whole notion of the love affair with yourself, like you said, which I imagine for

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:31.000
[Amit Varma]: everyone would be a love-hate relationship. Brings me to the question of the construction

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.240
[Amit Varma]: of the self. Like if I may quote from one of your pieces, you've written an excellent

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:38.760
[Amit Varma]: article and all the pieces I refer to will be linked from the show notes. Quote, being

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:44.560
[Amit Varma]: yourself is often sold to us as something ineffable, as if there is a virgin self, noble

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:49.520
[Amit Varma]: and unadulterated found in the departmental store of life between Auroville mindfulness

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:55.000
[Amit Varma]: and vintage chic, which we must find and display for best results. Stop quote. And this really

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.680
[Amit Varma]: spoke to me because it's always struck me that you know what all these self help books

00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:03.120
[Amit Varma]: talk about being true to yourself and finding yourself and being authentic and all of that

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:08.800
[Amit Varma]: is sort of circling around the central question of what are we it's not that all of us are

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:12.880
[Amit Varma]: unique. I mean, I tend to think that all of us are fundamentally the same. We are not

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.600
[Amit Varma]: blank slates because we are all hardwired in different but very similar ways. And obviously,

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.720
[Amit Varma]: we are brought up very differently and go through different influences. But rather than

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:27.120
[Amit Varma]: searching for an authentic self, I think it is more, perhaps, a wise to search for the

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:31.320
[Amit Varma]: best self that you can be after you define yourself. And this you know, when you from

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:36.160
[Amit Varma]: the point of view of growing up, for example, just thinking aloud, it seems to me that children

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:41.160
[Amit Varma]: at the time we grew up would have a lot more space to themselves to think about stuff and

00:16:41.160 --> 00:16:47.880
[Amit Varma]: to find what interests them and where they want to do. Whereas now perhaps the anxieties

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:53.440
[Amit Varma]: that are ubiquitous in modern lives are onto them much earlier than they used to be. And

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:58.240
[Amit Varma]: they're anxious to please their parent, they're anxious to please their peers on social media,

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:03.460
[Amit Varma]: they're anxious to be validated and get notifications and retweets and so on. And dealing with anxiety

00:17:03.460 --> 00:17:07.720
[Amit Varma]: is something that I think you will have to do anyway in an adult life. But now it comes

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:09.520
[Guest]: much earlier than it otherwise would.

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:13.560
[Guest]: It does. And I think like the fact that you're always supposed to be present for somebody

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:20.080
[Guest]: else's gaze, really, it's disturbing, you know, because it creates a distortion of yourself.

00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:24.600
[Guest]: And I have to say that I don't think it's bad to be present for somebody else's gaze.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:33.640
[Guest]: I think this seeing and being seen is not just a social kind of thing. It's also a profound

00:17:33.640 --> 00:17:39.880
[Guest]: human exchange that when two people meet each other, they see something about each other.

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:44.720
[Guest]: That's what makes conversations really happen, right? I mean, the fact is that like why is

00:17:44.720 --> 00:17:50.440
[Guest]: dating in India such an arduous thing? It's because people don't really have much by way

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:55.200
[Guest]: of the art of conversation going on for them, right? So there can be a dullness about or

00:17:55.200 --> 00:18:00.240
[Guest]: a kind of by rote feeling about so many exchanges, because you're not really seeing the other

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:04.240
[Guest]: person and nor are you showing something of yourself. I mean, another version of this

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:09.280
[Guest]: is like sometimes women will say that I dress for myself. And they're saying it's reactively

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:14.680
[Guest]: because otherwise you're scrutinized so much for the way that you look as a woman. But

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:19.440
[Guest]: I think it's all right. It's all right to dress for yourself, but also to dress to please

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:23.440
[Guest]: others, also to dress to attract others. That is part of the exchange. Life is all about

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:30.840
[Guest]: yourself and others, yourself in the world, right? But I think that to be locked into

00:18:30.840 --> 00:18:36.600
[Guest]: one thing where you can't withdraw from other people's gaze. Yes, I think that it's a terrifying

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:42.800
[Guest]: thought for me. So maybe I note it more when it's happening. But I think what I noticed

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:48.080
[Guest]: is that, you know, I began living on my own when I was 22 and it was very, very important

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:52.840
[Guest]: for me and not in a Virginia Woolf room of one's own kind of way, although it turned

00:18:52.840 --> 00:19:00.240
[Guest]: out that that's a very important truth. But I mean, I just want I didn't want to share

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:04.880
[Guest]: a place with anybody. I lived very poor in tenement housing, but I knew I had to be on

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:11.760
[Guest]: my own. And of course, I got some of the snide stuff from my relatives, not my own family,

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:16.440
[Guest]: but my extended family about, well, obviously, if a girl wants to live on her own completely,

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:20.200
[Guest]: what is it for? It's because she wants to mess around with boys. And I did want to mess

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:25.400
[Guest]: around with boys, of course. But I also just wanted not to be scrutinized all the time.

00:19:25.400 --> 00:19:30.800
[Guest]: I didn't want to account for every minute of my thoughts and movements. I just wanted

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:36.200
[Guest]: to come and go as I pleased. It was very hard being 22 or 23 and living on your own with

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:40.080
[Guest]: very little money. Even simple things like I didn't know how to cook properly and, you

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:44.760
[Guest]: know, I didn't have a fridge. There were a lot of logistical things you learn to navigate.

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:49.940
[Guest]: But it was the most important thing I ever did for myself because, yes, by being completely

00:19:49.940 --> 00:19:55.120
[Guest]: on my own, I figured myself out. And it takes such a long time to do that. So if young people

00:19:55.120 --> 00:20:00.160
[Guest]: don't have that space to even start that journey. And we live in a society that is so social

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:04.160
[Guest]: and so family oriented and people are so keen on marriage. When are you going to get that

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:10.480
[Guest]: time? Right. So I feel, yes, that we do need to worry about maybe not social media so much

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:14.920
[Guest]: because I think that if you have that sense of a relationship with yourself, it gives

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:19.120
[Guest]: you a resilience vis-a-vis social media as well. I don't think you become as dependent

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:25.320
[Guest]: on that validation if you are given the time and you learn to make it important to yourself.

00:20:25.320 --> 00:20:28.760
[Amit Varma]: But how many people have that? And also what it strikes me and you've written about this

00:20:28.760 --> 00:20:33.240
[Amit Varma]: very eloquently about, you know, how it's changed through the decades is just how one

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:38.120
[Amit Varma]: navigates relationships in the sense that like what you correctly said is that, you

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:41.800
[Amit Varma]: know, one of my favorite writers, Georges Simenon, the French author, once said that

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:46.880
[Amit Varma]: the fundamental problem in all his work was how one person can communicate anything to

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:51.080
[Amit Varma]: another person. We are all in a sense strangers to each other, which at one sense is bizarre

00:20:51.080 --> 00:20:55.360
[Amit Varma]: because we're all in a sense the same. But when you speak about the, you know, the problems

00:20:55.360 --> 00:21:00.640
[Amit Varma]: of communication between men and women in modern India, which is especially acute outside

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:06.320
[Amit Varma]: elite circles, where there are so many anxieties, crippling anxieties and all of that. And it

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:09.440
[Amit Varma]: strikes me that it's so tragic. You have a boy and a girl sitting with each other and

00:21:09.440 --> 00:21:15.240
[Amit Varma]: the boy is essentially dating a vision of the person he wants to be with and vice versa.

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:19.880
[Amit Varma]: And they don't know the real person. And when the real people collide, it inevitably results

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:24.040
[Amit Varma]: in heartbreak and you can live in that kind of denial and delusion all your life.

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:27.760
[Guest]: You can. And I think so much of it also has to do with the fact that life is broken down

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:32.960
[Guest]: and that's not a new thing, but it's exacerbated now. Life is just like broken down into milestones

00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:37.640
[Guest]: and goalposts, right? So you're just very anxious about getting to the next goalpost.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:41.240
[Guest]: And that also in the dating scenario gets replicated, right? Like, am I going to get

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:44.600
[Guest]: to first place? Am I going to get to second place? Am I going to do this? Is this going

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:48.560
[Guest]: to be a real thing? Is this going to be no strings attached? What is it? Like constantly

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:54.480
[Guest]: worrying about what it is rather than figuring out what you're feeling at that moment, right?

00:21:54.480 --> 00:22:00.200
[Guest]: So experiential things are not encouraged in our society. I remember that there was

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:04.880
[Guest]: a young woman who was part of a television show that I made and she had come away from

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:10.080
[Guest]: Meerut to be an actress in Bombay. And, you know, I mean, she didn't have much of a chance

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:18.320
[Guest]: of it. And then at some point she met Honey Singh at some awards function. I didn't even

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:21.400
[Guest]: know who Honey Singh was at the time we were making it. And in fact, I mean, one piece

00:22:21.400 --> 00:22:25.360
[Guest]: of footage, she's dancing to something and I'm like, wow, this music is really awesome

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:29.000
[Guest]: that she's dancing to it. And my colleague was like, that's Honey Singh. And I'm like,

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.880
[Guest]: oh my God, isn't that the person that everybody hates? But you know, the fact that she loved

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:38.840
[Guest]: his music and she got to meet him. And that was kind of like the excitement of the Bombay

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:42.960
[Guest]: dream that you may not become the actress, but you can still meet your idol. So there

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:48.480
[Guest]: was a magical quality. And it was a show in which women shot their own lives on video

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:53.200
[Guest]: for about a year. So she, you know, I remember she met Honey Singh at the awards function

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:57.920
[Guest]: and then she goes with a friend on the bike, on bandstand. And she's so happy that this

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:02.640
[Guest]: has happened to her. And she calls her mom and she's like, Mom, do you know what? I met

00:23:02.640 --> 00:23:07.400
[Guest]: Honey Singh today. And her mother says, what's the use of that? And her face collapses and

00:23:07.400 --> 00:23:16.360
[Guest]: she says, I mean, I was feeling happy. But what's the point of it? How does it matter?

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:21.080
[Guest]: What's it going to add up to? It's something that we find a lot that we have to account

00:23:21.080 --> 00:23:26.080
[Guest]: for. You repeatedly have stories of young people telling you that my parents don't care

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:30.440
[Guest]: that I found a job that I really, really enjoy. They just are like, oh, are you going to be

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:36.480
[Guest]: able to buy a house at x date? Are you able to do that? So now if that's what you're boiled

00:23:36.480 --> 00:23:37.480
[Guest]: down to,

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:41.480
[Guest]: You could say she has an innocence by your definition, and they've lost it.

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:47.400
[Guest]: In fact, in fact, I remember that in one of the scenes, she was waiting for an audition

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:51.560
[Guest]: and she started talking to another boy who was at the audition. And she asked him, how

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:58.880
[Guest]: old are you? And he said, 21. And she said, innocent. I loved the way she said it so much.

00:23:58.880 --> 00:24:04.320
[Guest]: So I also do frequently that were innocent. So but yes, she had that innocence, I have

00:24:04.320 --> 00:24:08.520
[Guest]: to say, and maybe that's why what attracted me to as a character that she had the exuberance

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:13.960
[Guest]: to be happy, to allow life to surprise and delight her even in the shittiest of circumstances.

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:18.160
[Guest]: She was also willing to be in the shittiest of circumstances, because she imagined that

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:19.160
[Guest]: something good might happen.

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:20.160
[Amit Varma]: Which film was this and when was this?

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:24.560
[Guest]: It wasn't a film, it was a series that I did for Zee TV called Connected Hamtam. And it

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:29.320
[Guest]: was about five women at a turning point in their lives, real life women, who shot their

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:34.600
[Guest]: own lives with a video camera for one year. And then we made like these 65 thematic episodes

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:35.600
[Guest]: with it.

00:24:35.600 --> 00:24:36.600
[Guest]: And when was this?

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:37.600
[Guest]: 2013, I think.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:38.600
[Guest]: Oh, okay. Have you met her since?

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:44.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've been in touch with her. It's been a while. She's still the same. She's still

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:48.760
[Guest]: the same. And it's pretty remarkable, right? Because she still hasn't become an actress.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:50.320
[Guest]: But she still thinks she might.

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:53.880
[Amit Varma]: The interesting thing about Honey Singh is though a lot of his music and lyrics are misogynist

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:58.480
[Amit Varma]: and he is whatever they say is a specific rape song that was attributed to him was actually

00:24:58.480 --> 00:24:59.480
[Amit Varma]: fake news.

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:00.480
[Amit Varma]: It was by another band.

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:05.600
[Guest]: But he is misogynist. And I think like, the outrage against his lyrics, you know, I feel

00:25:05.600 --> 00:25:11.760
[Guest]: divided about it. But I do think that, you know, if performers can be encouraged to think

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:16.520
[Guest]: outside the box, because these are also by rote formats, right, that you're gonna write

00:25:16.520 --> 00:25:18.960
[Guest]: about a girl like this, and you're gonna do this, but you can actually write something

00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:23.720
[Guest]: completely different, because a lot of it is also about the music and the kind of rhythmic

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:25.440
[Guest]: quality of the lyrics, right?

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:29.960
[Amit Varma]: But just thinking aloud, I guess, in an artistic sense, the more successful you are, the more

00:25:29.960 --> 00:25:34.240
[Amit Varma]: you're incentivized to play it safe. Because if something has brought you there, boy meets

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:38.320
[Amit Varma]: girl songs have brought you there, why would you try something different, you know, and

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:42.360
[Amit Varma]: therefore, you only try to do different things where you're not successful. So whatever,

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:43.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, you

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:47.160
[Guest]: I mean, I think there's some truth in that. I think that only people who the people who

00:25:47.160 --> 00:25:51.440
[Guest]: create newness and change are always the people who don't, who are not in the system already,

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:56.360
[Unknown]: right, who are not the beneficiaries. So that really brings us back to why dhariwala men

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:01.640
[Guest]: are so predictable and boring, why they'll always really imagine that the utterly boring

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:06.400
[Guest]: thing they've said is worth saying. It's because the system has rewarded them endlessly, right,

00:26:06.400 --> 00:26:12.120
[Guest]: for just being guys. And so there's no challenge to that. Of course, the challenge has come

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:14.560
[Guest]: because you are seeing a complete change in gender relationship.

00:26:14.560 --> 00:26:19.840
[Guest]: The challenges come from you. I mean, just dhariwala columnist versus non dhariwala columnist.

00:26:19.840 --> 00:26:22.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm presuming you include me among dhariwala columnists.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:23.480
[Unknown]: I don't know about that.

00:26:23.480 --> 00:26:26.480
[Unknown]: Yeah, now you're going to be polite.

00:26:26.480 --> 00:26:28.480
[Amit Varma]: I refuse to come into all this.

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:29.480
[Amit Varma]: Okay, that's okay.

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:36.040
[Guest]: No, I'm just saying that, like, there is a shift, right? There are so many kinds of,

00:26:36.040 --> 00:26:40.960
[Guest]: I mean, it's not just about women, like the entire trans community poses a complete rethink

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:45.760
[Guest]: to how we talk about gender and how we talk about each other for that matter. And I know

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:52.080
[Guest]: that sometimes political correctness feels like too much of a schlep. And it feels like,

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:56.640
[Guest]: oh, but you know, you're being too persnickety. But the thing is, it is the thing that brings

00:26:56.640 --> 00:27:01.560
[Guest]: a shift in our way of looking at things, right? And whenever somebody tells me that, oh, it's

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:06.400
[Guest]: so difficult to use the pronoun they, like, what's the big deal? But you know, there was

00:27:06.400 --> 00:27:10.120
[Guest]: a time when nobody, I remember that when I would say, please don't write miss, write

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:18.240
[Guest]: miss for me, people would be like, they'd roll their eyes. See, this is what I mean.

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:25.080
[Guest]: Boys love puns, but boys who will become men with beards. I used to always say I want a

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:30.280
[Guest]: t-shirt that says Pushpa, I hate puns because boys are often subjected to the unending puns

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:33.600
[Amit Varma]: and I'd be like, stop it, stop it. I don't often do this, but anyway, you've caught me

00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:41.360
[Guest]: in a weak moment. If you say so. So I think that there is a challenge posed to that way

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:47.600
[Guest]: of being and thinking. And I think those people who embrace the challenge will do something

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:52.520
[Guest]: fantastic and new. And those who don't embrace the challenge, but who become sulky in the

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:57.560
[Guest]: face of the challenge or say that I'm being attacked and what do you people know? You

00:27:57.560 --> 00:28:03.600
[Amit Varma]: will just keep doing the same old thing and become obsolete. So choose. Yeah, no. And

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:08.840
[Amit Varma]: what strikes me is that look, the universal anxiety that we all have and that humans have

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:13.240
[Amit Varma]: their hard wire to have is the anxiety to be loved, to be validated by others, right?

00:28:13.240 --> 00:28:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you keep constructing yourself in response to what you think others would

00:28:17.760 --> 00:28:22.000
[Amit Varma]: appreciate in you. You might define the others differently from people around you, but whatever

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:26.440
[Amit Varma]: you construct yourself that another thing is when society is changing so fast. And when

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:31.960
[Amit Varma]: the preferences of society are changing so fast, that also means that that constant reconstruction

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:36.720
[Amit Varma]: of the self also then has to gather us, you know, then the requirement for that gathers

00:28:36.720 --> 00:28:41.880
[Amit Varma]: a certain velocity. And I can totally see a lot of people, including men with beards,

00:28:41.880 --> 00:28:46.480
[Amit Varma]: including, you know, middle aged people like me, who are just then the reflexive responses

00:28:46.480 --> 00:28:49.640
[Amit Varma]: to say, no more, you know, you know, what is this shit?

00:28:49.640 --> 00:28:53.480
[Guest]: I mean, I think change is overwhelming, you know, change inside you and change outside

00:28:53.480 --> 00:29:00.600
[Guest]: you is overwhelming. But maybe it also means making a different relationship to time. And

00:29:00.600 --> 00:29:07.120
[Guest]: I would stress again, a different relationship to yourself. I think I have a friend who feels

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:15.520
[Guest]: annoyed by the way that I seem to keep shifting subjects I work on, because I do get interested

00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:19.920
[Guest]: in a topic for a very long time, right? Like, I worked on a lot of things about the city

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:24.280
[Guest]: for an extremely long time. But just when writing about Bombay and making films about

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:27.960
[Guest]: Bombay became a cool thing, it felt like I shifted focus.

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:31.680
[Amit Varma]: You made a film trying to find Sandra from Bandra. Everybody watch it, please link from

00:29:31.680 --> 00:29:36.600
[Guest]: the show notes. Yeah, so I'm thinking you're a rabbit hole person. I'm a rabbit hole person.

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:39.640
[Guest]: As in you find a subject you like and you go down the rabbit hole. Yeah, but I go down

00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:43.080
[Guest]: the rabbit hole is the correct way, actually, because it's not like I'm not a completist.

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:47.680
[Guest]: I won't read all the books by writer and because I'm not a boy, I'll not get all the albums.

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:53.920
[Guest]: But I'm definitely willing to go down the rabbit hole and see what will happen. And

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:59.080
[Guest]: then once like the full pleasure of it has been experienced for me. And there must be

00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:04.360
[Guest]: something perverse that when the really big rewards start coming in, because now that

00:30:04.360 --> 00:30:07.880
[Guest]: thing has become more established as an idea and more people are working on it, I start

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:12.160
[Guest]: to lose interest in it. And I don't feel like doing it anymore. Now, this might just be

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:16.240
[Guest]: my personality quirk. But I think that saved me from some of the things that you're talking

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:20.040
[Guest]: about right now. So my friend who's annoyed with me, he calls me bunky Julia because he's

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:24.080
[Guest]: like the closer success comes to you, the more inside the forest you want to go and

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:29.240
[Guest]: like investigate some new Florida and fauna. And I'm like, Yeah, but imagine I get to do

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:34.160
[Guest]: it. So there are many ways to define success. One would be that I just sit in the same damn

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:41.720
[Guest]: tree until the turn of the tree comes around, right? Or the other is that I really like

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:46.240
[Guest]: I've worked for 30 years doing a number of very different things. I have not conformed

00:30:46.240 --> 00:30:49.240
[Guest]: to this idea of the brand, right, that you just do one thing in one way, and then you

00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:53.400
[Guest]: become really, really successful. And no, I'm not really successful in that sense. But

00:30:53.400 --> 00:30:57.160
[Guest]: for me, the definition of success is that I want to do certain things. And I get to

00:30:57.160 --> 00:31:00.480
[Amit Varma]: do them. And there's a memorable line from one of your columns that seems to express

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:05.080
[Amit Varma]: this where you talk about how the treadmill has been sold as a journey. Yes. And you've

00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:09.400
[Amit Varma]: basically said that no, you know, I'm not getting on one of these treadmills. I'm going

00:31:09.400 --> 00:31:14.240
[Guest]: deeper into the forest. And you know, it's because I have a great annoyance and dislike

00:31:14.240 --> 00:31:23.320
[Guest]: of being bored. Like I cannot tolerate boredom of the kind that comes from pretense. So I

00:31:23.320 --> 00:31:27.760
[Guest]: don't mean like sitting at a railway platform for three hours is unbearable. On days it

00:31:27.760 --> 00:31:31.840
[Guest]: may be unbearable on days it's pretty okay to drift off. But that thing that you make

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:36.760
[Guest]: me watch a movie that is just pretentious. Yeah, it's like there's nothing new in it.

00:31:36.760 --> 00:31:42.200
[Guest]: It's just pontificating. Or somebody writes the same old politically correct posturing

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:47.000
[Guest]: kind of novel that I'm supposed to hail it as the great new piece of political writing.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:50.640
[Amit Varma]: I refuse. In fact, you've created a hashtag that sort of sums all this up. Why don't you

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:55.880
[Guest]: share it with us? Yes, I want to make this hashtag famous. Hashtag bore mat kar yaar.

00:31:55.880 --> 00:32:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Social media, please find ways to make this hashtag famous because it applies to

00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest]: so much. Right. And I also think that if people refuse to be bored, the world will have a

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:10.640
[Guest]: lot more like lively work, you know, I think that actually, I feel the hashtag very political,

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:16.200
[Guest]: because I see so many people do a lot of boring work, but still get to be in really important

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:20.200
[Guest]: places, you know, like you'll see the same filmmakers in the same kind of film and everybody's

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:25.760
[Guest]: trashing the films, but they're again making those kinds of films. And the same opportunities

00:32:25.760 --> 00:32:30.480
[Guest]: that are writers, there are columnists, there's all kinds of things. And it is privilege.

00:32:30.480 --> 00:32:34.840
[Guest]: The very fact that you have gender and caste and class on your side means that you get

00:32:34.840 --> 00:32:38.920
[Guest]: the right to bore other people. And I think you can boil it down to a very simple experience

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:43.480
[Guest]: that of going to a family dinner. And there's always one uncle who bores you, you know,

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:48.360
[Guest]: better let me tell you. And then they'll start telling you about, you know, whatever, whatever

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:52.320
[Guest]: is a new course, they don't even know anything about it, but they will start to tell you.

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:56.160
[Guest]: And I used to always get angry when this used to happen. I used to leave the table, I used

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:59.080
[Guest]: to say, abo kuch nahi pata, my parents would be like, you can't talk like that. And I'm

00:32:59.080 --> 00:33:03.960
[Guest]: like, he can't talk like that. I know more about it than him. So this insubordination

00:33:03.960 --> 00:33:07.960
[Guest]: wasn't coming out of rudeness or any kind of youthful hotheadedness. It is just like,

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:13.120
[Guest]: how can you bore me? Because that boringness is coming out of your right to oppress me.

00:33:13.120 --> 00:33:17.480
[Guest]: You are taking up my time. You don't think that you have to charm me, please me, engage

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:22.280
[Guest]: with me. That is boredom, right? That you think I'm not there. I just have to be this

00:33:22.280 --> 00:33:25.760
[Guest]: blank and captive audience to whatever you throw my way.

00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:31.080
[Amit Varma]: But then, you know, that brings up an interesting question, which is that, does that mean that,

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:35.920
[Amit Varma]: for example, a filmmaker who wants a film to unwind at its own pace, like say, a Tarkovsky

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:40.600
[Amit Varma]: or a Bellator or whatever, is boring you and is not conscious enough of entertaining the

00:33:40.600 --> 00:33:41.600
[Guest]: audience as you say?

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:46.200
[Guest]: No, I don't think that boredom is the opposite of entertainment in the conventional sense,

00:33:46.200 --> 00:33:52.680
[Guest]: right? To engage me, to challenge me is to not bore me. Even when I said earlier that

00:33:52.680 --> 00:33:57.360
[Guest]: the idea that you would show me the same hackneyed thing, the hackneyed thing pretending to be

00:33:57.360 --> 00:34:02.520
[Guest]: new is a thing I can't bear. And we have too much of that around. Somebody is supposed

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:08.800
[Guest]: to be a cutting edge filmmaker who's not like that. That edge won't even cut butter. So

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:13.480
[Guest]: I just feel like I don't want to. I don't want to be part of receiving any of that.

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:19.640
[Guest]: I won't see those films. Like now, because I'm older, I also have a new column called

00:34:19.640 --> 00:34:25.640
[Guest]: Life is Short, by column I don't mean writing column, but like it's a section in my invisible

00:34:25.640 --> 00:34:29.280
[Guest]: notebook that I'm not seeing that film because life is short. I'm not going to do that because

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:35.760
[Guest]: life is short. But to engage us, to make us see the world differently, like a Tarkovsky,

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:42.120
[Guest]: classical music, Drupad, these are difficult things to learn and to enter sometimes, not

00:34:42.120 --> 00:34:46.040
[Guest]: always. But I think the invitation to the entry is full of, there is a passion, there's

00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:50.480
[Guest]: an intelligence, there's a challenge to me. I don't mind being challenged. I may even

00:34:50.480 --> 00:34:54.960
[Guest]: come out saying that didn't really work for me, but I don't mind if there is that honesty

00:34:54.960 --> 00:35:00.920
[Guest]: of that artist really wanting to do something, really having something to say. Right. So

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:05.200
[Guest]: I obviously don't mean that's something that is like, I met somebody the other day who

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:08.280
[Guest]: said like, you know, people don't have an attention span for more than six minutes now.

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:12.360
[Guest]: So the ideal length for a video is, or it should be 25 minutes, which every listener

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:16.720
[Guest]: of the scene in the unseen knows is utter bullshit. It is bullshit because you know,

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:22.520
[Guest]: I think films are as long as they need to be. And they could be very long and very short.

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: So I have made films 13 minutes long. I have made films 95 minutes long. I mean, I make

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.360
[Guest]: the film till the film is there. And I've had people watch the long films and the short

00:35:32.360 --> 00:35:37.400
[Guest]: films. Somebody can feel bored in a 10 minute film also. I frequently felt bored in a 10

00:35:37.400 --> 00:35:41.160
[Amit Varma]: minute film. You can feel bored in 30 seconds. Just to sort of pick up one of the phrases

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:44.840
[Amit Varma]: you use, which was hackneyed. And I'm again thinking aloud here. But you know, when I

00:35:44.840 --> 00:35:49.480
[Amit Varma]: was a cricket writer, a decade and a half ago, and one of my constant bugbears was that

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Indian writers use so many effing cliches in their writing, you know, like Martin Amis

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:58.280
[Amit Varma]: titled one of his books, a war against cliche and cliches are obviously the biggest. And

00:35:58.280 --> 00:36:01.800
[Amit Varma]: it happens far more in cricket. And after a while, I realized that no, wait a minute,

00:36:01.800 --> 00:36:05.880
[Amit Varma]: it's not because they don't know. Or it's not because they can't think outside cliches.

00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:08.720
[Amit Varma]: It's because especially in places like the Hindu where this post writing was supposed

00:36:08.720 --> 00:36:13.880
[Amit Varma]: to be very good and was extremely bad and cliche ridden. And you know, verbose and flowery

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:19.360
[Amit Varma]: and cliche ridden. And, and I realized that it is a virtue to know as many cliches as

00:36:19.360 --> 00:36:26.640
[Amit Varma]: you can, as for example, you know, Ravi Shastri does or Sidhu does, or whatever, you know,

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:33.080
[Amit Varma]: when I was blogging back on the blogspot version of India Uncut in perhaps circa 2005 2006,

00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:37.520
[Amit Varma]: I started documenting Shastri's cliches well before anybody else. And it came to more than

00:36:37.520 --> 00:36:41.720
[Amit Varma]: 100 posts, I think, because, you know, it would just think I don't know much about Shastri.

00:36:41.720 --> 00:36:46.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And, and I find this problem in films also, though, I am obviously not as educated

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:52.040
[Amit Varma]: in terms of films, as you are to be able to speak about it. But I find it one, the problem

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:58.440
[Amit Varma]: of avoiding cliches is harder in films. Because if you typically set up a scene in a particular

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:02.960
[Amit Varma]: way, it almost like becomes a convention ki pehle long shot fir mid shot, koi baat kar

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:07.080
[Amit Varma]: raha hai to close up, stuff like that. How do you avoid those cliches, which are perhaps

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:12.160
[Amit Varma]: harder to avoid, but all other kinds of cliches, like the way a story unfolds, or whatever.

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:16.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, am I right in saying that the cliche is a bigger problem in Indian popular culture?

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:21.040
[Guest]: So I think that there is, I don't know if the cliche is a bigger problem. I don't I

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:25.440
[Guest]: mean, like, see, right now, there are the protests going on, and people are writing

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:32.760
[Guest]: poems at like a high, high rate. slogans are amazing. Yeah. And you're seeing so much newness.

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:38.080
[Guest]: You're seeing a real absence of cliches. Otherwise, you know, protests when you were younger,

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:41.920
[Guest]: like we used to cringe because they were a they were a location of cliches. And so much

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:47.000
[Guest]: of political language has been ridden by political cliche. But I would like to argue that one

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:50.560
[Guest]: can look at this occurrence of what you're calling cliche in two different ways. One

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:56.440
[Guest]: is that certainly in India, or Indian culture, Indian social culture, there seems to be a

00:37:56.440 --> 00:38:02.800
[Guest]: great comfort derived from saying something which everybody knows. And there's a deep suspicion

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:09.880
[Guest]: of the person who is saying something that seems not so familiar. But more so if that

00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:13.640
[Guest]: person is trying to say that I'm better than you, because I'm saying something not so familiar,

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:20.560
[Guest]: right? So yes, the joke, which we all know, will always make a group of people crack up.

00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:24.000
[Guest]: And we always feel like, I mean, there'll be those of us who feel like this is a cliche

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:28.400
[Guest]: joke where people laughing at it. But there is something about like a kind of community

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:33.160
[Guest]: culture, where saying things which everybody knows, makes me seems to make urban middle

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:38.440
[Guest]: class people feel comfortable. So there's one type of cliche operating there. The other

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:44.160
[Guest]: is writing artistic production, where you do not expect to find cliche, you know, which

00:38:44.160 --> 00:38:50.480
[Guest]: is supposed to be the place where cliches are killed. So the new things can be made

00:38:50.480 --> 00:38:54.760
[Guest]: are so comfortably cliched, which I think does have a lot to do with privilege. Because

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:59.960
[Guest]: really, if a lot of your work and I'll take documentary film as an example, I think that

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:04.480
[Guest]: so much of Indian documentary filmmaking, there have been some great filmmakers here.

00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:08.240
[Guest]: And I don't even want to preface the word doc filmmaking with documentary filmmaking

00:39:08.240 --> 00:39:13.520
[Guest]: as if it's not a film, I feel very irritated with those who say, I'm going to make a film.

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:17.480
[Guest]: And they always mean fiction feature. But really, a documentary is also a film.

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:20.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, this is why in my introduction, I specifically made sure I referred to you

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:22.640
[Guest]: as a filmmaker, not as a documentary film.

00:39:22.640 --> 00:39:29.160
[Guest]: Yeah. So I mean, the thing is, I make documentaries and documentaries are a kind of film. But

00:39:29.160 --> 00:39:34.840
[Guest]: I think that while there's been like tremendously exciting work done in Indian documentary,

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:38.920
[Guest]: you also have had a convention of the political documentary, which says the same things in

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:44.200
[Guest]: the same way forever and ever. And it is more a demonstration of your political position

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:49.480
[Guest]: than a real exploration of an idea from your political perspective. These are two different

00:39:49.480 --> 00:39:54.280
[Guest]: things, right? So I feel like the first, which is just demonstrating your political position,

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:56.360
[Guest]: is simply a reiteration of your privilege.

00:39:56.360 --> 00:40:00.840
[Amit Varma]: Can you illustrate that? I mean, not with specific people or so on, but you know.

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:06.640
[Guest]: So, you know, for example, I would say that there'll be a roster of topics of importance.

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:10.640
[Guest]: And communalism has always been on top of the list. If you want to show that you're

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:15.560
[Guest]: communal, you have to be anti-communal. So, for example, speaking about feminism, it's

00:40:15.560 --> 00:40:22.920
[Guest]: not that high on the list. It's not considered to be that important. So similarly, having

00:40:22.920 --> 00:40:28.560
[Guest]: a film which will not have a commentary is considered to be a purer kind of filmmaking

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:33.560
[Guest]: because you're letting the people speak in their own voices. These are certain cliches

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:39.720
[Guest]: of filmmaking. They're not cliches when they started out. They came from a very particular

00:40:39.720 --> 00:40:46.040
[Guest]: place that the technology of cinema made it possible for us to record interviews. And

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:50.600
[Guest]: why should I impose what something means onto you? But after some time, it just becomes

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:55.440
[Guest]: a stock fashion of shooting something. You know, I'm not even really thinking about this.

00:40:55.440 --> 00:41:00.240
[Guest]: I will make a film in which people will speak in their own voices. They will only fit into

00:41:00.240 --> 00:41:05.440
[Guest]: a schema of what is liberal and not liberal. But by making that film, what is really happening,

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:10.040
[Guest]: I am showing that I am liberal. And because I am liberal, I should have the privilege

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:14.600
[Guest]: to decide things for others. And my way of saying should rule the country. So a lot of

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:20.720
[Guest]: the enterprise of documentary film was too closely entangled with the idea of the nation

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:26.200
[Guest]: state and how the nation state should be. So either it's critiquing the nation state

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:31.640
[Guest]: or it is with films division expressing the desires of the nation state. In contrast to

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:40.840
[Guest]: that, what you do have in the late 90s and early 2000s is a kind of like an efflorescence

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:45.640
[Guest]: of filmmaking approaches where somebody is making a film about their parents. Somebody

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:52.480
[Guest]: is making a film about body image. I made a film about feminism and what it means to

00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:57.880
[Guest]: me. So you're actually seeing suddenly that documentary becomes a way to express yourself

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:05.360
[Guest]: creatively and politically. And that gets rid of some of the cliches. So what I want

00:42:05.360 --> 00:42:11.200
[Guest]: to say actually is that a cliche in form or cliche in work is really a cliched way of

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:18.080
[Guest]: thinking. It presents something that is otherwise considered to be a cliche suddenly seems fresh

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:22.920
[Guest]: when it is located in a different way of thinking. And I would say we should also be careful

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:27.240
[Guest]: to distinguish between cliches and conventions. I don't think that conventions are automatically

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:32.160
[Guest]: bad things. I think the convention becomes a cliche when the filmmaker is not really

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:36.400
[Guest]: thinking or the artist is not really thinking why they want something in their film, right?

00:42:36.400 --> 00:42:41.320
[Guest]: So I'll give you an example in film criticism. One of the things that you frequently find

00:42:41.320 --> 00:42:47.560
[Guest]: people saying in India is, oh, you know, it's Indian films are inferior because they have

00:42:47.560 --> 00:42:54.000
[Guest]: song and dance. People are running around trees. This idea that realism makes a film

00:42:54.000 --> 00:43:00.560
[Guest]: more rational, that it makes it superior and serious. And therefore, it's an art film and

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:04.960
[Guest]: that's what we should aspire to. I think this is such a primitive way to think about something.

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:09.200
[Guest]: You know, realism is only an aesthetic because everything is a lie. Everything that we make

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:14.640
[Guest]: is a construction. So realism is a kind of way in which I make the film. And fantasy

00:43:14.640 --> 00:43:15.960
[Amit Varma]: is another way in which I might make the film.

00:43:15.960 --> 00:43:19.040
[Amit Varma]: You're never realistic. You're just pretending to be realistic is what you're saying. And

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:21.640
[Guest]: therefore, it has as much artifice only expressed differently.

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:27.000
[Guest]: So realism is an artifice, the same way that when you say, oh, today is Desi day. So today

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:31.600
[Guest]: you wear a saree. As if to say you are not Desi on the rest of the days, but you are

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:36.600
[Guest]: Desi and your dress is as Desi as a saree in some senses. Is English and Indian languages

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:42.000
[Guest]: one of those same discussions, right? So what is considered to be the norm and what is considered

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:48.160
[Guest]: to be the oddity or the exception then has a lot to do with who is in a place of privilege

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:52.240
[Guest]: or what ideas are being privileged, right? So the idea that we now have to shake off

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:58.880
[Guest]: this Desi-ness, it's like having some kind of an accent in your English that you have

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:03.680
[Guest]: songs in your film, right? That makes the film somehow infradig. I feel this is really

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:09.120
[Guest]: cliche thinking because in fact, the presence of the songs is an act of great sophistication

00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:14.280
[Guest]: in filmmaking. It's the poetic with the prosaic, right? It's a place of emotion. It's a place

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:18.880
[Guest]: of eroticism. We've had great poets write songs in Hindi films. You have amazing song

00:44:18.880 --> 00:44:24.520
[Guest]: picturizations. The height of sophistication of Hindi filmmaking is in the songs. The height

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:30.800
[Guest]: of stupidity is in the criticism that says, Oh my God, these songs. So, you know, a stupid

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:38.080
[Guest]: gaze can destroy something beautiful so quickly. And the stupid gaze often comes with just

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:41.920
[Guest]: privilege, which doesn't recognize that there are other ways of looking at the world. And

00:44:41.920 --> 00:44:45.720
[Guest]: that's why that gaze is always destined to become obsolete. The person who retains their

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:50.840
[Guest]: innocence in a way, which is to say that I could be wrong. I could change the way I think.

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:54.000
[Guest]: There is no danger in changing the way I think because I'm not clinging to my privilege at

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:57.760
[Guest]: all costs. That person is not going to become obsolete because they will always be open

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:02.040
[Guest]: to the new thing, feel delighted by it, and then employ it in their work, right? So I

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:08.840
[Guest]: think that's the kind of cliche tendency which creates boringness. So we now will have very

00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:14.240
[Guest]: boring films or very retrograde films in their thought, which look realistic. So now everybody

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:19.160
[Guest]: will say it's very good. And, you know, it's these are the people who will put India in

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:22.960
[Guest]: the international scene. Why do we care so much about the international scene? Like who's

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:26.720
[Guest]: gaze that's performing for somebody else's gaze? I mean, we've got a massive country

00:45:26.720 --> 00:45:31.680
[Guest]: with massive audiences. I think we're pretty okay. So, you know, that's why I love Shahrukh

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:34.040
[Guest]: Khan because Shahrukh Khan is like, no, I care about the Indian audience.

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:38.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is fascinating because I was talking about cliches and cricket writing in popular

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:43.440
[Amit Varma]: culture. And you sort of expanded my gaze on cliches, by pointing out that cliches can

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:49.520
[Amit Varma]: apply to ideology and politics as well. And what it boils down to is that, you know, another

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:52.880
[Amit Varma]: way of thinking about this is that look, the world is deeply complicated. So we have to

00:45:52.880 --> 00:45:57.800
[Amit Varma]: explain it to ourselves by making up stories about it, by building frames through which

00:45:57.800 --> 00:46:01.940
[Amit Varma]: we can look at the world and things make sense. And we build those frames. And those frames

00:46:01.940 --> 00:46:07.280
[Amit Varma]: give us a certain comfort and therefore become a cliched way of thinking. And especially

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:13.680
[Amit Varma]: in modern, we start to assume they are normal. Yeah, yeah, right. And that seems to be especially

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:17.280
[Amit Varma]: hardened in modern times by two things. One is, of course, social media has the effect

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:22.000
[Amit Varma]: of drawing us into echo chambers and what Cass Sunstein calls group polarization, where

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:26.160
[Amit Varma]: within groups who agree with us, we become increasingly more extreme than we already

00:46:26.160 --> 00:46:31.520
[Amit Varma]: were and more hardened. And the other also is that, you know, I feel incredibly thankful

00:46:31.520 --> 00:46:36.240
[Amit Varma]: that 25 years ago, there was no Twitter, because I would have said and done the stupidest things.

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And then, because I have put something out in public, I would have felt compelled out

00:46:40.680 --> 00:46:46.200
[Amit Varma]: of ego to double down on it. And that could actually have become my hardened position,

00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:50.760
[Amit Varma]: almost forced by the gaze of others that once I have said this, and then people attack me,

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:54.920
[Amit Varma]: and then I double down on it. And then I find a tribe that agrees with the original thing

00:46:54.920 --> 00:46:59.300
[Amit Varma]: I said, and soon I am part of the tribe and any independent thinking I could subsequently

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:03.160
[Amit Varma]: have done, sort of vanishes. And that's, that's something that worries me.

00:47:03.160 --> 00:47:08.360
[Guest]: Do you think that really you never had hardened positions before Twitter, in your peer group?

00:47:08.360 --> 00:47:12.960
[Amit Varma]: Of course I did. But I think they arose gradually. And I also think that the early positions

00:47:12.960 --> 00:47:19.160
[Amit Varma]: I had when I was in college, might have hardened, I'm speculating, might have hardened, had

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:23.960
[Amit Varma]: I actually taken positions on them in social media, and joined a particular ideological

00:47:23.960 --> 00:47:27.200
[Amit Varma]: tribe or the other, and then I would never have been able to leave.

00:47:27.200 --> 00:47:30.400
[Guest]: Maybe I don't know. But I think that, you know, already the previous discussion we were

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:36.640
[Guest]: having tells us that maybe social media amplifies what is already out there. But I do think

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:43.480
[Guest]: that there are so many people who choose something very early in life, and then stick to it,

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:50.120
[Guest]: no matter what, even if they're miserable, stay in bad marriages, in awful jobs, because

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:53.580
[Guest]: I think that's what they ought to do. They've said that this is what they are, and now they

00:47:53.580 --> 00:47:55.120
[Amit Varma]: cannot possibly abandon it.

00:47:55.120 --> 00:47:58.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a sunk cost fallacy plus the inertia of life.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:03.760
[Guest]: Inertia of fear, what else is out there, plus great dependence on how other people see you.

00:48:03.760 --> 00:48:07.160
[Guest]: So I think like this hardening of positions, first of all, I think in youth, we all do

00:48:07.160 --> 00:48:12.760
[Guest]: it to some extent or the other. So for example, a common example of it is when two people

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:18.760
[Guest]: you know who are romantically involved fall out with each other, right? And say you've

00:48:18.760 --> 00:48:22.680
[Guest]: never liked your friend's boyfriend. And then she's like, he's this way and he's that way.

00:48:22.680 --> 00:48:26.000
[Guest]: You're like, yeah, I always felt he's this way. I'm so relieved you're not seeing him.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:30.960
[Guest]: After one week, they get back together. It's over, right? Like you're out of the picture.

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:39.920
[Guest]: Because to some extent, so I think it's the fact that people feel like they want to disconnect

00:48:39.920 --> 00:48:43.680
[Guest]: themselves from that position which they had. That's one way. So they harden the position

00:48:43.680 --> 00:48:47.640
[Guest]: for the boyfriend. No, I never said that. You were the one who was saying this, whatever,

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:51.640
[Guest]: that would be one. The other thing is that once they have said he's horrible, they're

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:57.500
[Guest]: unable to go back to the person because they have said he's horrible, right? So this tendency

00:48:57.500 --> 00:49:03.200
[Guest]: to harden the position, I think it's a human tendency. I do think that, yeah, because social

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:09.960
[Guest]: media is so amplified and social media rewards you fast. You have reason to stick with very

00:49:09.960 --> 00:49:14.640
[Guest]: silly type of things. But I don't think it's any different than real life. The fact that

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:21.760
[Guest]: you won't leave a marriage, relationship, job, career choice, house, family that's cruel

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:27.200
[Guest]: to you, whatever, all of these things. I mean, when you see the show The Crown, you often

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:31.280
[Guest]: wonder why Princess Margaret doesn't just give everyone a kick and go off. But she's

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:37.620
[Guest]: just embedded in that royal family, its privileges, and wanting their approval despite the immense

00:49:37.620 --> 00:49:43.040
[Guest]: cruelty to her. So I feel like actually that happens. And social media has created different

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:46.960
[Guest]: types of cultural capital and rewarding very quickly. So it's very difficult for you to

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:53.560
[Guest]: leave those rewards, but it is exactly the same as life. And in other words, I have also

00:49:53.560 --> 00:49:58.480
[Guest]: seen people on social media change their positions over time. I have seen them become different.

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:03.680
[Guest]: I have been trolled a couple of times very badly online quite some time ago before it

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:09.680
[Guest]: was such a common thing. And because it was not so common, it was traumatic for me. And

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:15.600
[Guest]: the first time around, I cried. I felt like I'll never recover from it. It felt very,

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:21.960
[Guest]: very serious. But I think the impact that it had on me actually was, A, I thought very

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:29.080
[Guest]: hard about why it had happened. I felt there was even, I didn't agree with it, but I didn't

00:50:29.080 --> 00:50:34.320
[Guest]: disagree with the essential political thought that it emerged from. And actually, because

00:50:34.320 --> 00:50:38.600
[Guest]: I suffered so much from its cruelty, it did change a little bit the way I began to write

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:43.280
[Guest]: about other people. So I feel in the long run, it did change me, and it did change my

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:47.160
[Guest]: positions. Since I'm not a person who takes a lot of, like, I don't spend a lot of my

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:51.040
[Guest]: time online, I don't express myself online in the same way. Perhaps I'm not the right

00:50:51.040 --> 00:50:56.160
[Guest]: person to talk about it. But I do feel that this interactivity with others can yield many

00:50:56.160 --> 00:51:00.480
[Guest]: selves. And I have seen other people also change the way that they are. I don't think

00:51:00.480 --> 00:51:08.680
[Guest]: it's impossible. But and I do think that through this very, you know, like, hyperkinetic format

00:51:08.680 --> 00:51:13.840
[Guest]: that we're in, we will also reach a place of conversation, which is more reasonable,

00:51:13.840 --> 00:51:14.840
[Amit Varma]: I hope.

00:51:14.840 --> 00:51:17.720
[Amit Varma]: No, and I don't want to be an old man with beard railing against social media. And oh,

00:51:17.720 --> 00:51:18.720
[Guest]: look what the young...

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:19.720
[Guest]: No, you love social media.

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I love social media. And one of the things that I think it gives us is an escape

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:27.600
[Amit Varma]: from cliche. Because we are exposed to newer kinds of thinking than we otherwise would

00:51:27.600 --> 00:51:31.840
[Amit Varma]: have been newer forms of art than we otherwise would have been. And that sort of changes

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:36.160
[Amit Varma]: everything. So I kind of came into this episode thinking, okay, there are three big themes,

00:51:36.160 --> 00:51:42.360
[Amit Varma]: I guess we'll talk about, which are feminism, documentary filmmaking, and desire and sexuality.

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And instead, we've had this delightfully digressive chat, which we will continue, which I'm very

00:51:47.080 --> 00:51:51.720
[Amit Varma]: happy. This is exactly I think my listeners will agree, this is exactly how a good conversation

00:51:51.720 --> 00:51:56.400
[Amit Varma]: should be. And we shall continue after the break and also get to those three topics.

