02:44:33.640 --> 02:44:37.640
[Guest]: and thoughtful way. If you haven't seen it, please check it out, folks who are listening.

02:44:37.640 --> 02:44:41.480
[Amit Varma]: Agentsofishq.com, the link, of course, will be on the show notes.

02:44:41.480 --> 02:44:45.640
[Guest]: Yes. And also, I think one of the things we've done is a lot of cutting-edge work on consent,

02:44:45.640 --> 02:44:50.040
[Guest]: like cutting edge in the world, because we made this Lavani about consent, which is, first of all,

02:44:50.040 --> 02:44:54.440
[Guest]: very entertaining and awesome, but also because it said that consent is not just about the binary of

02:44:54.440 --> 02:44:59.640
[Guest]: yes and no, but it's about yes, no, and maybe. And I do think that the maybe space is very important

02:44:59.640 --> 02:45:06.120
[Guest]: generally as a feminist, because the idea that somebody will take time to decide is the most

02:45:06.120 --> 02:45:09.880
[Amit Varma]: fearful thing for us all. In fact, one very evocative phrase I learned from you was a

02:45:09.880 --> 02:45:12.120
[Guest]: garden of consent. Yes, the garden of consent.

02:45:12.120 --> 02:45:17.080
[Amit Varma]: Which is a space where everything is fluid. It's not necessarily a yes or a no. And you've even,

02:45:17.080 --> 02:45:22.200
[Amit Varma]: in a separate place, spoken about relationships and dating, for example, as more of an exploration.

02:45:22.200 --> 02:45:27.240
[Amit Varma]: So it's not a goal-oriented thing, by end of first date, I must get to this base or that base.

02:45:27.240 --> 02:45:30.120
[Amit Varma]: But you have to think of it as an open-ended exploration, which,

02:45:30.120 --> 02:45:32.920
[Guest]: and there are so many modern anxieties. I mean, there'll be many people who'll

02:45:32.920 --> 02:45:38.040
[Guest]: have the experience on Tinder of somebody not wanting to meet them unless sex is guaranteed.

02:45:38.040 --> 02:45:43.880
[Guest]: And I have often said to such people that, you know, you may be worried whether I will sleep

02:45:43.880 --> 02:45:47.160
[Guest]: with you or not, but how do you know you will want to sleep with me when you meet me? I mean,

02:45:47.160 --> 02:45:51.160
[Guest]: it's a question not only about what you're getting from the other person, but thinking about what you

02:45:51.160 --> 02:45:55.640
[Guest]: really want, which I think people don't do because they're so anxious about achieving that goal.

02:45:55.640 --> 02:45:59.880
[Guest]: And there's a fantastic piece on agents of ish written by an Indian woman of Caribbean origin

02:45:59.880 --> 02:46:03.560
[Guest]: called Flirting Without Agendas. And it's about appreciating each other,

02:46:03.560 --> 02:46:07.480
[Guest]: not about flirting in order to get something, which is what you're saying the goal.

02:46:07.480 --> 02:46:12.040
[Guest]: So I think like there are all of these very beautiful ideas that conform more to the way

02:46:12.040 --> 02:46:16.360
[Guest]: that we actually wish to live life, if we may or may not always be living it that way,

02:46:16.360 --> 02:46:22.680
[Guest]: that I think makes it also, it's an important project, I think, because it dares to say many

02:46:22.680 --> 02:46:27.480
[Guest]: things that people feel, but are scared to say out loud. And it could not have been done without

02:46:27.480 --> 02:46:31.640
[Guest]: the very strong feminist grounding that it has, right? So it centers the experience of women

02:46:31.640 --> 02:46:36.120
[Guest]: and queer people first. Men are not the center of the conversation. Their experiences are not

02:46:36.120 --> 02:46:40.600
[Guest]: what drives the idea of what is liberation. Liberation is different for each person is

02:46:40.600 --> 02:46:45.960
[Guest]: what we believe. And everybody's ability and possibility to define their own sexual journeys

02:46:45.960 --> 02:46:50.680
[Guest]: is what qualifies as liberation. If you really, really feel you are monogamous, then you are

02:46:50.680 --> 02:46:55.400
[Guest]: liberated if you live that life. And if you're really and truly polyamorous, you're liberated

02:46:55.400 --> 02:47:00.520
[Guest]: if you can live that life, right? So there's no one liberation. I Love Latika is a project that I

02:47:00.520 --> 02:47:08.520
[Guest]: did purely for pleasure and joy for myself. It's a digital interactive project where there is vine

02:47:08.520 --> 02:47:14.040
[Guest]: with many, many different kinds of flowers and fruits. Many are not realistic. And when you

02:47:14.040 --> 02:47:19.800
[Guest]: click on it, on any fruit, it opens, either it becomes a flower or it starts like oozing pulp

02:47:19.800 --> 02:47:25.560
[Guest]: and many erotic things like that. And it plays a poem, an audio clip of a poem, which is an erotic

02:47:25.560 --> 02:47:31.400
[Guest]: poem from an old one, a new one from different places in the world. So it's actually just that.

02:47:31.400 --> 02:47:37.480
[Guest]: It's like a little room surrounded by a diaphanous curtain that you go into and you just look at all

02:47:37.480 --> 02:47:45.080
[Guest]: these gorgeous and surreal flora and fauna and listen to erotic poems. And while watching people

02:47:45.080 --> 02:47:50.520
[Guest]: play with the Love Latika, I felt very much that people love poetry. They don't know they love it

02:47:50.520 --> 02:47:56.200
[Guest]: sometimes, but poetry should be read out and spoken so that people can develop a personal

02:47:56.200 --> 02:48:00.920
